{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","author_sig":"{\"payload\": \"\", \"payloadType\": \"application/vnd.rebar.authorship.v1+json\", \"signatures\": [{\"keyid\": \"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d\", \"sig\": \"\"}]}","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Invalidate downstream plan reviews after upstream plan-material changes\n\n## Problem\nA plan-review attestation can remain valid after a direct child or prerequisite changes its plan. In a large epic or dependency chain, an agent can therefore claim or close work using assumptions that no longer match the plans it relies on. The existing material fingerprint protects only the reviewed ticket itself; it does not bind the reviewed plan to the current material of related tickets.\n\n## Outcome\nEvery new plan review records signed plan-material pins for the ticket's direct children and direct prerequisites. A pin binds the related ticket's canonical ID, its role, and its current narrow material fingerprint. When enforcement is enabled, material drift in a pinned ticket invalidates the downstream attestation. Propagation is deliberately natural rather than eager: an upstream change invalidates its direct dependent; farther downstream tickets invalidate only if the intermediate ticket adapts materially.\n\n## Settled design\n\n### Material and relationships\n- Material remains the current narrow definition: description and acceptance criteria, file impact, and direct-child IDs.\n- Attestation validity is not propagated. A related ticket's review can be invalid without affecting downstream tickets when its material did not change.\n- Direct prerequisites are the union of outgoing depends_on targets and inbound blocks sources. Stored relation types are unchanged; aliases and short IDs are resolved before use.\n- Parent/child review behavior already exists and is not changed by this epic. Children participate only in material pinning.\n\n### Signed plan-material pins\n- New plan reviews always emit one unique plan-material-pin per direct child or prerequisite, keyed by authoritative canonical ticket ID and normalized role child or prerequisite.\n- Pins reuse the existing material fingerprint format. Pin collection is all-or-nothing: unresolved, malformed, duplicate, or unreadable required targets prevent signing.\n- Pins are automatic signed attestation metadata. There is no new CLI or MCP operation and no first-order ticket field.\n- Legacy attestations without pins remain valid. No migration or eager backfill is performed; the next ordinary re-review adds pins.\n- Archived tickets remain readable. A pinned target that has been deleted or is missing makes the pin stale and requires relationship repair followed by re-review.\n\n### Enforcement and rollout\n- verify.enforce_plan_material_pins defaults to false. Pin drift remains visible but advisory while disabled; valid remains true.\n- Re-enabling enforcement immediately applies existing pin-aware attestations. It never rewrites pins, while legacy unpinned attestations continue to pass.\n- Pin validity is applied consistently to claim, close, attestation reuse, drift refresh, re-sign, audit, and derived health.\n- New reviews emit pins in every project regardless of enforcement configuration. The rebar project enables enforcement.\n\n### Execution reviews and close gate\n- Entering in_progress establishes execution mode. Execution mode persists across later statuses and resets only when the ticket returns to open.\n- Planning attestations carry review-phase: planning. Execution attestations carry review-phase: execution and priority-floor: 0.80. Phase-less legacy attestations count as planning.\n- Planning mode accepts planning attestations only. Execution mode accepts planning attestations or compatible execution attestations.\n- During execution, each blocking criterion uses max(its normal threshold, 0.8). Advisory-only criteria stay advisory, deterministic structural failures stay blocking, and lower-priority findings remain visible.\n- verify.require_plan_review_for_close defaults to false. When enabled, task, story, and epic close operations require a current certified plan review. Bugs, session logs, code reviews, identities, and idea-to-closed transitions remain exempt.\n- Close performs no LLM review. A failed gate directs the agent to run review-plan separately.\n- Close checks signature, compatible phase, the ticket's own material, relationship pins, and other non-code attestation validity, but intentionally ignores file dependency hashes and whole-HEAD freshness because implementation normally changes impacted files.\n- The existing force-close with a non-empty reason bypasses completion and close-time plan-review gates with an audit record. Structural child-closure rules remain non-bypassable.\n- Review snapshots phase, material, and pins before the LLM call and rechecks them before signing. Close prechecks before completion verification and rechecks under the store write lock before writing STATUS.\n\n### Prerequisite consistency review\n- A specialized criterion runs deterministically when direct prerequisites exist. General reviewers do not receive prerequisite material.\n- The criterion receives the subject plan and the current narrow material of each prerequisite; existing parent/child criteria and prompts are unchanged.\n- Multiple prerequisite evaluations may share a call when whole prerequisite blocks fit within existing context headroom. Batching is an optimization only: each evaluation asks whether the subject is consistent with one prerequisite.\n- Every prerequisite receives an explicit disposition, and every blocking finding identifies exactly one canonical prerequisite ID. Unattributed findings are indeterminate and cannot block.\n- Pass 2 receives the same subject/prerequisite pairing and verifies substance and attribution. Findings then use normal Pass 3 decisions and the execution floor.\n- Context-limit failures retry with smaller bins. Subject plus one oversized prerequisite yields the existing too-large remediation.\n- Packed behavior is fidelity-tested against one-prerequisite-per-call for recall, false acceptance, and attribution.\n\n### Health and documentation\n- Derived pin and review-phase health appears in detailed CLI show, MCP ticket detail, audit output, close errors, and the web ticket-review UI. Ordinary list output remains unchanged.\n- Health is derived at read time; no warning event is persisted. When enforcement is off, the UI labels drift advisory.\n- plan-material-pin is documented in advanced attestation/gate documentation, not basic user documentation.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] New plan-review attestations deterministically contain complete, canonical plan-material pins for all direct children and prerequisites, while legacy unpinned attestations remain valid.\n- [ ] Optional pin enforcement invalidates every pin-aware attestation consumer on actual related-ticket material drift and stays advisory when disabled.\n- [ ] Execution-phase reviews apply the 0.8 floor and the optional close gate requires a separate current review without treating implementation file changes as plan drift.\n- [ ] Direct prerequisites receive a focused, token-budget-batched consistency review with per-ID coverage, verified attribution, and measured fidelity against one-per-call review.\n- [ ] Detailed CLI, MCP, audit, close-error, and web surfaces explain derived pin/phase health without changing ordinary list output.\n- [ ] Rebar enables both enforcement flags and end-to-end lifecycle tests cover toggling, legacy compatibility, natural transitivity, deletion, execution adaptation, concurrency, and force-close behavior.\n\n## Not in scope\n- Consolidating or migrating depends_on and blocks storage.\n- Changing existing parent/child review criteria or injecting relationship context into every reviewer.\n- Eager graph-wide or transitive invalidation events.\n- Persisted invalidation warnings or a new user-facing pin command.\n- Backfilling or rewriting existing attestations.\n","title":"Invalidate downstream plan reviews after child or prerequisite material changes"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784517350178230001,"uuid":"afa1574d-fdcb-422e-a959-d6569dd4d48a"}